    {
      "title": "Reduction to standard forms",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Reduction of General Equation to standard forms&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>General equation of straight line is given by $\\text{Ax}+\\text{By}+\\text{c}=0$. Now we will try &amp; reduce this to our standard forms</p><p><strong>(1) To 'slope-intercept' form:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>we know that slope intercept form is</p><p>$\\text{y}=\\text{mx}+\\text{c}$</p><p>redistributing the standard equation</p><p>$y=-\\left( \\frac{A}{B} \\right)x-\\left( \\frac{C}{B} \\right)$</p><p>where $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ m}=\\left( \\frac{-\\text{A}}{\\text{B}} \\right)\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\And \\text{c }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }=-\\left( \\frac{\\text{C}}{\\text{B}} \\right)$</p><p><strong>(2) To 'Intercept' form&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Rearranging standard form into intercept form which is</p><p>$\\frac{x}{a}+\\frac{y}{b}=1$</p><p>$A x+B y=-C$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow$ $\\frac{A x}{-C}+\\left(\\frac{B}{-C}\\right) y=1$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow$ $\\frac{\\mathrm{x}}{\\left(-{ }^{\\mathrm{C} / \\mathrm{A}}\\right)}+\\frac{\\mathrm{y}}{(-\\mathrm{C} / \\mathrm{B})}=1$</p><p>where</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; \\text{a}\\left( \\text{x-intercept }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ } \\right)=\\frac{-\\text{C}}{\\text{A}} \\\\ {} &amp; \\text{b}\\left( \\text{y-intercept }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ } \\right)=\\frac{-\\text{C}}{\\text{B}} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p><strong>(3) Reduction to 'Normal' form&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Normal form: $\\text{xcos}\\alpha +\\text{ysin}\\alpha =\\text{p}$</p><p>Standard form: ax $+by+c=0$</p><p>arranging, $ax+by=-c$</p><p>dividing by $\\sqrt{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}$</p><p>$\\frac{-a}{\\sqrt{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}}x+\\frac{-b}{\\sqrt{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}}y=\\frac{+c}{\\sqrt{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}}$</p><p>WHY we divided by $\\sqrt{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}$</p><p>See in normal form</p><p>${{(\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ coeff}\\text{. }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }x)}^{2}}+{{(\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ coeff}\\text{. }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }y)}^{2}}=1$</p><p>so now if we see</p><p>$\\begin{matrix} {{\\left( \\frac{-a}{\\sqrt{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}} \\right)}^{2}}+{{\\left( \\frac{-b}{\\sqrt{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}} \\right)}^{2}}=\\frac{{{a}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}+\\frac{{{b}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}=1 \\\\ \\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }x\\text{cos}\\alpha +y\\text{sin}\\alpha =\\left( \\frac{-a}{\\sqrt{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}} \\right)x+y\\left( \\frac{-b}{\\sqrt{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}} \\right)=c \\\\ \\end{matrix}$</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddc8c03b9dcaf1afecbd"
    },
    {
      "title": "Angle of line with other line",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Lines making an angle </strong>θ <strong>with a given line&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>In general, there can be 2 lines making an angle $\\theta $ with a given line.</p><p>$\\text{L}$ : the given line with slope $\\text{m}$</p><p>${{\\text{l}}_{1}}{{\\text{l}}_{2}}$ the two lines making an angle of $\\theta $ with $\\text{L}$slopes ${{\\text{m}}_{1}}\\And $ ${{\\text{m}}_{2}}$ respectively.</p><p>Then the slopes ${{\\text{m}}_{1}}\\And \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{2}}$ can be obtained by the following formula.</p><p>${{\\text{m}}_{1}}=\\frac{\\text{m}-\\text{tan}\\theta }{1+\\text{mtan}\\theta },{{\\text{m}}_{2}}=\\frac{\\text{m}+\\text{tan}\\theta }{1-\\text{mtan}\\theta }$ or vice versa.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"272\" height=\"176\"></p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddc8c03b9dcaf1afecbe"
    }
  ],
